# Git ignore rules for an alexandria collection.
#
# This repo holds the textual backbone of your collection: catalog metadata,
# item READMEs, notes, and skill configuration. Binary content (PDFs, images,
# audio, video) and the generated wiki are excluded on purpose — those are
# backed up via /coll-backup, not through git.
#
# See docs/guides/backing-up-your-collection.md for the full two-track story.

# Generated output and caches — regenerated on demand, no value in tracking
wiki/
.venv/
__pycache__/
.ruff_cache/
.mypy_cache/
.pytest_cache/
*.pyc
*.pyo

# Per-machine state — specific to the machine you're on, not shared across clones
.claude/state/
.alexandria-backups/

# OS metadata
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db

# Sensitive files — never track these by default. If you genuinely need to
# version-track a file matching one of these patterns, explicitly add it
# with `git add -f <path>`. The friction is intentional.
.env
.env.*
*.key
*.pem
*.pfx
*.p12
credentials*
secrets*
id_rsa*
id_ed25519*
.aws/
.ssh/
.gnupg/

# Binary content — backed up via /coll-backup, not git. Personal photos,
# PDFs, audio, video, and auto-discovered thumbnails live with your items
# but don't need version history. If you want a binary file to be tracked,
# explicitly add it with `git add -f <path>`.
*.pdf
*.epub
*.mobi
*.jpg
*.jpeg
*.png
*.heic
*.webp
*.gif
*.mp3
*.flac
*.wav
*.m4a
*.ogg
*.mp4
*.mov
*.mkv
*.webm

# Scouts — each scout is its own git repo. Entries below are added
# automatically by /coll-new-scout and /coll-scout when scouts are created
# or imported. Do not edit by hand; use those skills.
